  "prompt": "Which non Arabic speaking countries use Arabic at the UN or other international conferences, meetings and summits?",
  "response": "Several non-Arabic speaking countries use Arabic as an official language in international conferences, meetings, and summits, particularly at the United Nations and other international organizations. These countries often have significant historical, cultural, or diplomatic ties to the Arab world. \n\nHere are some examples:\n\n1. **Israel**: While Hebrew is the official language of Israel, Arabic is also recognized as a language with a special status. At the UN, representative documents are often provided in Arabic.\n\n2. **Iran**: Persian (Farsi) is the official language, but Iran uses Arabic in various contexts, particularly in relation to Islamic discourse and regional diplomacy.\n\n3. **Turkey**: Turkish is the official language, but Turkey engages with Arabic in diplomatic contexts, especially within organizations that include Arab states.\n\n4. **Malaysia**: Malay is the official language, but Arabic plays a significant role due to the country\u2019s strong Islamic identity and participation in various Islamic conferences.\n\n5. **Indonesia**: While Indonesian is the official language, Arabic has considerable influence due to the country\u2019s large Muslim population and cultural relations with Arab nations.\n\n6. **Pakistan**: Urdu is the national language, but Arabic is often used in religious, educational, and diplomatic contexts, particularly concerning Islamic collaboration.\n\nThese countries participate in Arabic-speaking forums and may offer documents in Arabic or have Arabic translations available during conferences, even if Arabic is not the primary language of the nation.",
